<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="225" pageId="1" pageNumber="224" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[106,227,1587,1611]" box="[106,227,1587,1611]" pageId="1" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[106,227,1587,1611]" pageId="1" pageNumber="224">Etymology:</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[106,1097,1625,1650]" lastBlockId="2.[189,1180,1449,1657]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="225" pageId="1" pageNumber="224">
<materialsCitation country="Iran" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="225" location="Zagros Mountains" pageId="1" pageNumber="224" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Tehran">
The specific epithet is the classical name for what is known today as the ruins of Rayy in 
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1093,1626,1649]" name="Iran" pageId="1" pageNumber="224">Iran</collectingCountry>
. Rayy lies inside of the greater metropolitan area of 
<collectingRegion box="[718,790,1449,1473]" country="Iran" name="Tehran" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Tehran</collectingRegion>
and was built by the Median Empire approximately 5000 years ago. The Greeks called the area comprising modern 
<collectingRegion box="[1008,1112,1480,1504]" country="Iran" name="Kordestan" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Kurdistan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion country="Iran" name="Azarbayjan-e Sharqi" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Azerbaijan</collectingRegion>
, and northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[462,504,1511,1534]" name="Iran" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Iran</collectingCountry>
(roughly 
<collectingRegion box="[612,696,1511,1535]" country="Iran" name="Esfahan" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Esfahan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[710,815,1511,1535]" country="Iran" name="Hamadan" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Hamedan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[827,902,1511,1535]" country="Iran" name="Tehran" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Tehran</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[916,992,1511,1535]" country="Iran" name="Zanjan" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Zanjan</collectingRegion>
, and neighboring provinces around the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03EC87C785409966CCDBE1CEFDBBFD31:8E9A600A85439967CDF5E667FDD1F9D4" box="[411,604,1541,1566]" country="Iran" name="Zagros Mountains" pageId="2" pageNumber="225" stateProvince="Tehran">Zagros Mountains</location>
, although the ancient Median Empire at times extended further south in modern 
<collectingCountry box="[444,486,1573,1596]" name="Iran" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Iran</collectingCountry>
and as far east as Kashmir) “Medea” or “Media” [the Latin adjective of which is 
<emphasis box="[304,378,1603,1627]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">median</emphasis>
(“in the middle”), and for which 
<taxonomicName authority="ENGEL" authorityName="ENGEL" box="[716,946,1603,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="225" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediana">
<emphasis box="[716,873,1603,1627]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">Osmia mediana</emphasis>
ENGEL
</taxonomicName>
from nearby Karaj was named], and the people of the region, the Medes
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4779369" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4779369" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4779369/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="225" startId="2.[198,236,1376,1398]" targetBox="[198,1173,174,1369]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[198,1174,1376,1427]" pageId="2" pageNumber="225">
